{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1775838793774,"sessionID":"ses_287c2af5affeyN4a421B18EChw","part":{"id":"prt_d783d902c001MBmIR70Lbx40E3","messageID":"msg_d783d7b97001f7zhjRZyl7eHxs","sessionID":"ses_287c2af5affeyN4a421B18EChw","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775838795124,"sessionID":"ses_287c2af5affeyN4a421B18EChw","part":{"id":"prt_d783d9372001vK6ipGDmJkxZXg","messageID":"msg_d783d7b97001f7zhjRZyl7eHxs","sessionID":"ses_287c2af5affeyN4a421B18EChw","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_tool-5d3aa8b737594ccba0afca7188ffc701","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/sandbox-orchestration/spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/sandbox-orchestration/spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Sandbox Orchestration Specification\n2: \n3: ## Purpose\n4: Orchestrate agent sandboxes via Kubernetes CRDs (AgentRuntime, CodeInterpreter), a Gin HTTP API (workload manager), session persistence, garbage collection, and optional service-account authentication.\n5: \n6: ## Requirements\n7: \n8: ### Requirement: AgentRuntime CRD schema and API registration\n9: The system SHALL expose a namespaced `AgentRuntime` custom resource in API group `runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh`, version `v1alpha1`, with subresource `status`, print column `Age` from `.metadata.creationTimestamp`, and SHALL register list kind `AgentRuntimeList`.\n10: \n11: #### Scenario: Group version and resource naming\n12: - **GIVEN** a Kubernetes API client resolving the CRD\n13: - **WHEN** the group, version, and kind are read from type metadata\n14: - **THEN** `GroupVersion` is `runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh/v1alpha1`, kind `AgentRuntime`, and GVR resource name is `agentruntimes`\n15: \n16: ### Requirement: AgentRuntime spec fields and kubebuilder rules\n17: The system SHALL define `AgentRuntimeSpec` with: `Ports` as `[]TargetPort` serialized under JSON key `targetPort`; required `Template` (`*SandboxTemplate`) under JSON key `podTemplate`; required `SessionTimeout` (`*metav1.Duration`) under `sessionTimeout` with kubebuilder default `\"15m\"`; required `MaxSessionDuration` (`*metav1.Duration`) under `maxSessionDuration` with kubebuilder default `\"8h\"`.\n18: \n19: #### Scenario: SandboxTemplate embeds Pod spec\n20: - **GIVEN** an `AgentRuntime` with `spec.podTemplate`\n21: - **WHEN** the template is deserialized\n22: - **THEN** `labels` and `annotations` are optional maps and `spec` is required and of type `corev1.PodSpec`\n23: \n24: ### Requirement: AgentRuntime status\n25: The system SHALL define `AgentRuntimeStatus` with optional `conditions` of type `[]metav1.Condition`.\n26: \n27: #### Scenario: Conditions optional\n28: - **GIVEN** a minimal `AgentRuntime` object\n29: - **WHEN** status is omitted or empty\n30: - **THEN** deserialization succeeds without requiring `conditions`\n31: \n32: ### Requirement: CodeInterpreter CRD schema\n33: The system SHALL expose a namespaced `CodeInterpreter` CRD in the same API group/version with subresource `status` and print column `Age` from `.metadata.creationTimestamp`.\n34: \n35: #### Scenario: CodeInterpreter GVR\n36: - **GIVEN** dynamic client configuration for workload templates\n37: - **WHEN** GVR is constructed for `codeinterpreters`\n38: - **THEN** group is `runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh`, version `v1alpha1`, resource `codeinterpreters`\n39: \n40: ### Requirement: CodeInterpreterSpec fields\n41: The system SHALL define `CodeInterpreterSpec` with: optional `Ports` (`[]TargetPort`, JSON `ports`); required `Template` (`*CodeInterpreterSandboxTemplate`, JSON `template`); optional `SessionTimeout` with default `\"15m\"`; optional `MaxSessionDuration` with default `\"8h\"`; optional `WarmPoolSize` (`*int32`); optional `AuthMode` (`AuthModeType`, JSON `authMode`) with default `\"picod\"` and enum `picod` or `none`.\n42: \n43: #### Scenario: Auth mode constants\n44: - **GIVEN** API constants for auth mode\n45: - **WHEN** `AuthMode` is compared\n46: - **THEN** `AuthModePicoD` equals `\"picod\"` and `AuthModeNone` equals `\"none\"`\n47: \n48: ### Requirement: CodeInterpreterStatus fields\n49: The system SHALL define `CodeInterpreterStatus` with optional `conditions` and optional boolean `ready`.\n50: \n51: #### Scenario: Ready flag\n52: - **GIVEN** a reconciled `CodeInterpreter`\n53: - **WHEN** status is updated by the controller\n54: - **THEN** `status.ready` may be set to `true` alongside a `Ready` condition\n55: \n56: ### Requirement: TargetPort and Protocol types\n57: The system SHALL define `TargetPort` with optional `pathPrefix`, optional `name`, required `port` (`uint32`), and required `protocol` (`ProtocolType`) with kubebuilder default `HTTP` and enum `HTTP` or `HTTPS`.\n58: \n59: #### Scenario: Protocol constants\n60: - **GIVEN** port configuration without explicit protocol in some code paths\n61: - **WHEN** defaults apply at API level\n62: - **THEN** default protocol is `HTTP` per kubebuilder marker\n63: \n64: ### Requirement: Workload manager health endpoint\n65: The system SHALL serve `GET /health` without authentication and SHALL respond `200` with JSON body `{\"status\":\"healthy\"}`.\n66: \n67: #### Scenario: Health bypasses auth middleware\n68: - **GIVEN** `EnableAuth` is true\n69: - **WHEN** a client calls `GET /health` with no `Authorization` header\n70: - **THEN** the response status is 200 and body contains `\"status\":\"healthy\"`\n71: \n72: ### Requirement: Workload manager v1 routes and middleware\n73: The system SHALL mount a `/v1` route group with `loggingMiddleware` then `authMiddleware` (order preserved), and SHALL register `POST /v1/agent-runtime`, `DELETE /v1/agent-runtime/sessions/:sessionId`, `POST /v1/code-interpreter`, and `DELETE /v1/code-interpreter/sessions/:sessionId`.\n74: \n75: #### Scenario: Session id path parameter\n76: - **GIVEN** a delete request\n77: - **WHEN** Gin binds the path\n78: - **THEN** the session identifier is read from parameter name `sessionId` (camelCase)\n79: \n80: ### Requirement: Create sandbox request validation\n81: The system SHALL accept JSON for create endpoints matching `CreateSandboxRequest` with fields `kind`, `name`, `namespace`; SHALL overwrite `kind` from the handler (`AgentRuntime` or `CodeInterpreter`); and SHALL reject requests where `kind` is not one of those, `namespace` is empty, or `name` is empty.\n82: \n83: #### Scenario: Validation failure returns 400\n84: - **GIVEN** the handler sets `sandboxReq.Kind` from the route and `Validate()` is called\n85: - **WHEN** `namespace` or `name` is empty in the JSON body\n86: - **THEN** the response is 400 and the error message includes `required` (e.g. `namespace is required` or `name is required`)\n87: \n88: ### Requirement: Create sandbox success response\n89: On successful creation the system SHALL respond `200` with `CreateSandboxResponse` containing `sessionId`, `sandboxId`, `sandboxName`, and `entryPoints` (each entry point has `path`, `protocol`, `endpoint`).\n90: \n91: #### Scenario: Entry points reflect TargetPort and pod IP\n92: - **GIVEN** a sandbox reaches running state and pod IP is resolved\n93: - **WHEN** the response is built\n94: - **THEN** each entry point `endpoint` is `host:port` joined from pod IP and configured port, with protocol string from `TargetPort.Protocol`\n95: \n96: ### Requirement: Create sandbox error responses\n97: The system SHALL return `400` with `{\"message\":...}` for invalid JSON or validation failure; `404` with message from wrapped not-found errors when AgentRuntime or CodeInterpreter is missing from informer cache; `401` with message from client extraction error when `EnableAuth` is true; `500` with `{\"message\":\"internal server error\"}` for other create failures including timeout.\n98: \n99: #### Scenario: JSON parse failure\n100: - **GIVEN** a non-JSON body to `POST /v1/agent-runtime`\n101: - **WHEN** the handler binds JSON\n102: - **THEN** status is 400 and message is `Invalid request body`\n103: \n104: ### Requirement: Optional Bearer authentication via TokenReview\n105: When `EnableAuth` is true, the system SHALL require header `Authorization: Bearer <token>` with exactly two space-separated fields; SHALL validate via `authentication/v1` `TokenReview` create; SHALL cache results in an LRU cache (capacity 1000, entry TTL 5 minutes); and SHALL store in context: token, full username, service account name, namespace parsed from `system:serviceaccount:<ns>:<name>`.\n106: \n107: #### Scenario: Missing header\n108: - **GIVEN** `EnableAuth` is true\n109: - **WHEN** `/v1/...` is called without `Authorization`\n110: - **THEN** response is 401 with message `Missing authorization header` and handler chain aborts\n111: \n112: #### Scenario: TokenReview success path\n113: - **GIVEN** a valid service account token and `EnableAuth` true\n114: - **WHEN** `validateServiceAccountToken` runs with cache miss\n115: - **THEN** the server creates `TokenReview` with `spec.token` set and uses `status.user.username` when `status.authenticated` is true\n116: \n117: ### Requirement: Authenticated Kubernetes operations use user client\n118: When `EnableAuth` is true, the system SHALL use a per-user dynamic client (from bearer token) for creating/deleting `Sandbox` or `SandboxClaim` resources; when false, SHALL use the manager’s in-cluster/default dynamic client.\n119: \n120: #### Scenario: User client cache key\n121: - **GIVEN** repeated requests from the same namespace and service account name\n122: - **WHEN** `GetOrCreateUserK8sClient` is used\n123: - **THEN** the cache key is `<namespace>:<serviceAccountName>`\n124: \n125: ### Requirement: Sandbox creation ordering and store placeholder\n126: The system SHALL call `StoreSandbox` with a placeholder `SandboxInfo` before creating the `Sandbox` or `SandboxClaim` in the API; SHALL register a one-shot watcher before create; SHALL wait up to 2 minutes for sandbox status `running` from the reconciler; SHALL resolve pod IP and then `UpdateSandbox` with full info; and SHALL roll back the created CR on failure after the wait (delete Sandbox or SandboxClaim within a 30s timeout context).\n127: \n128: #### Scenario: Watcher registration before create\n129: - **GIVEN** a create request reaches `createSandbox`\n130: - **WHEN** the Sandbox CR is created\n131: - **THEN** `WatchSandboxOnce` was already invoked for that namespace/name\n132: \n133: #### Scenario: Timeout returns error\n134: - **GIVEN** no running notification within 2 minutes\n135: - **WHEN** the select completes\n136: - **THEN** creation fails with error `sandbox creation timed out` and HTTP 500 is returned to the client\n137: \n138: ### Requirement: Pod IP resolution\n139: The system SHALL prefer pod name equal to sandbox name; if annotation `agents.x-k8s.io/sandbox-pod-name` exists on the created Sandbox (from agent-sandbox controller), SHALL use that as pod name; SHALL load pod from informer cache and require `PodRunning` and non-empty `PodIP`; otherwise SHALL list pods by label `runtime.agentcube.io/sandbox-name=<sandboxName>` and pick the pod whose controller owner reference is kind `Sandbox` and name matches.\n140: \n141: #### Scenario: Pod not running yields error\n142: - **GIVEN** a matching pod in non-Running phase\n143: - **WHEN** IP is resolved\n144: - **THEN** resolution fails with an error indicating the pod is not running\n145: \n146: ### Requirement: Delete sandbox by session\n147: The system SHALL load session from store by `sessionId`; on `ErrNotFound` return `404` with message `Session ID <id> not found, maybe already deleted`; delete `SandboxClaim` when stored `Kind` is `SandboxClaim`, else delete `Sandbox`; treat API `NotFound` on delete as success; then `DeleteSandboxBySessionID`; success response `200` `{\"message\":\"Sandbox deleted successfully\"}`.\n148: \n149: #### Scenario: Store miss\n150: - **GIVEN** no session key in store\n151: - **WHEN** DELETE is invoked\n152: - **THEN** HTTP status is 404 and message mentions the session id\n153: \n154: ### Requirement: Garbage collection loop\n155: The system SHALL run a background goroutine tick every 15 seconds; each tick SHALL use a context timeout of 2 minutes; SHALL query inactive sessions with cutoff `now - 15m` and batch limit 16; SHALL query expired sessions with `before = now` and batch limit 16; SHALL merge lists and delete each unique workload then remove store entry by session ID.\n156: \n157: #### Scenario: GC uses DefaultSandboxIdleTimeout\n158: - **GIVEN** GC lists inactive sandboxes\n159: - **WHEN** computing the inactive cutoff\n160: - **THEN** `inactiveTime` equals `time.Now().Add(-DefaultSandboxIdleTimeout)` where `DefaultSandboxIdleTimeout` is 15 minutes\n161: \n162: ### Requirement: HTTP server and process behavior\n163: The system SHALL use Gin with `gin.New()` for the workload API; SHALL serve with `h2c` wrapping and `http2.Server`; SHALL use `ReadTimeout` 15s and `IdleTimeout` 90s for HTTP when not using TLS; SHALL ping the store before listening; SHALL sync informers (AgentRuntime, CodeInterpreter, Pod) with up to 1 minute wait; on SIGINT/SIGTERM SHALL shutdown HTTP within 15s, cancel context, wait for background workers, then `Close()` the store.\n164: \n165: #### Scenario: TLS requires cert and key\n166: - **GIVEN** `EnableTLS` is true and cert or key path is empty\n167: - **WHEN** `Start` runs\n168: - **THEN** it returns an error that TLS is enabled but cert/key not provided\n169: \n170: ### Requirement: API error helper constants\n171: The system SHALL define in package `api` the sentinel errors `ErrAgentRuntimeNotFound`, `ErrCodeInterpreterNotFound`, `ErrTemplateMissing`, `ErrPublicKeyMissing`, and SHALL map `CodeInterpreter` kind to group-resource `agentcube.volcano.sh/codeinterpreters` and default kinds to `agentcube.volcano.sh/agentruntimes` for `NewSandboxTemplateNotFoundError`.\n172: \n173: #### Scenario: Session not found uses API machinery\n174: - **GIVEN** `NewSessionNotFoundError(\"sid\")`\n175: - **WHEN** the error is inspected as `APIStatus`\n176: - **THEN** the group resource is `agentcube.volcano.sh, Resource=sessions` and name is the session id\n\n(End of file - total 176 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Sandbox Orchestration Specification\n\n## Purpose\nOrchestrate agent sandboxes via Kubernetes CRDs (AgentRuntime, CodeInterpreter), a Gin HTTP API (workload manager), session persistence, garbage collection, and optional service-account authentication.\n\n## Requirements\n\n### Requirement: AgentRuntime CRD schema and API registration\nThe system SHALL expose a namespaced `AgentRuntime` custom resource in API group `runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh`, version `v1alpha1`, with subresource `status`, print column `Age` from `.metadata.creationTimestamp`, and SHALL register list kind `AgentRuntimeList`.\n\n#### Scenario: Group version and resource naming\n- **GIVEN** a Kubernetes API client resolving the CRD\n- **WHEN** the group, version, and kind are read from type metadata\n- **THEN** `GroupVersion` is `runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh/v1alpha1`, kind `AgentRuntime`, and GVR resource name is `agentruntimes`\n\n### Requirement: AgentRuntime spec fields and kubebuilder rules\nThe system SHALL define `AgentRuntimeSpec` with: `Ports` as `[]TargetPort` serialized under JSON key `targetPort`; required `Template` (`*SandboxTemplate`) under JSON key `podTemplate`; required `SessionTimeout` (`*metav1.Duration`) under `sessionTimeout` with kubebuilder default `\"15m\"`; required `MaxSessionDuration` (`*metav1.Duration`) under `maxSessionDuration` with kubebuilder default `\"8h\"`.\n\n#### Scenario: SandboxTemplate embeds Pod spec\n- **GIVEN** an `AgentRuntime` with `spec.podTemplate`","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/sandbox-orchestration/spec.md","time":{"start":1775838795109,"end":1775838795123}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775838795127,"sessionID":"ses_287c2af5affeyN4a421B18EChw","part":{"id":"prt_d783d9559001L8COb4L3COO06d","messageID":"msg_d783d7b97001f7zhjRZyl7eHxs","sessionID":"ses_287c2af5affeyN4a421B18EChw","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_tool-51cc1866a63f4943965c820e7064f481","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/integrations/spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/integrations/spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Integrations Specification\n2: \n3: ## Purpose\n4: \n5: Normative requirements for the AgentCube Dify plugin integration and the PCAP analyzer example that uses AgentCube code interpreters and Kubernetes sandboxes.\n6: \n7: ## Requirements\n8: \n9: ### Requirement: Dify plugin bootstrap and runtime\n10: \n11: The system SHALL expose a Dify-compatible Python plugin whose process entry runs the framework runner with a configured maximum request timeout.\n12: \n13: #### Scenario: Plugin process starts\n14: \n15: - **GIVEN** the plugin package is installed with compatible `dify-plugin` and `agentcube-sdk` versions\n16: - **WHEN** the platform starts the plugin using the manifest-declared entrypoint\n17: - **THEN** the plugin SHALL execute `main` which runs `Plugin(DifyPluginEnv(MAX_REQUEST_TIMEOUT=120)).run()` until the host stops it\n18: \n19: ---\n20: \n21: ### Requirement: Plugin manifest structure\n22: \n23: The system SHALL ship a root `manifest.yaml` declaring plugin metadata, tool provider registration, resource permissions, and runner metadata sufficient for Dify to load and execute the plugin.\n24: \n25: #### Scenario: Required manifest fields\n26: \n27: - **GIVEN** a valid plugin package root\n28: - **WHEN** the manifest is parsed by a Dify-compatible toolchain\n29: - **THEN** the manifest SHALL include `version`, `type: plugin`, `author`, `name`, `label` (multilingual map), `description` (multilingual), `icon`, `icon_dark`, `resource` (including `memory` and `permission` subtree), `plugins.tools` listing provider descriptors, and `meta` containing `version`, `arch`, `runner` (`language`, `version`, `entrypoint`), and `minimum_dify_version`\n30: \n31: #### Scenario: Tool provider wiring\n32: \n33: - **GIVEN** the manifest `plugins.tools` references the Agentcube provider descriptor\n34: - **WHEN** the plugin is loaded\n35: - **THEN** Dify SHALL resolve `provider/agentcube.yaml` and associate it with the Python module declared under `extra.python.source`\n36: \n37: ---\n38: \n39: ### Requirement: Provider descriptor structure\n40: \n41: The system SHALL define a tool provider YAML that identifies the provider, lists its tools, and points to the Python provider implementation.\n42: \n43: #### Scenario: Provider lists tools and entry module\n44: \n45: - **GIVEN** `provider/agentcube.yaml` is present\n46: - **WHEN** the integration runtime resolves the provider\n47: - **THEN** the descriptor SHALL include `identity` (author, name, multilingual label/description, icon), a `tools` list including `tools/agentcube-code-interpreter.yaml`, and `extra.python.source: provider/agentcube.py`\n48: \n49: ---\n50: \n51: ### Requirement: Tool parameter schema\n52: \n53: The system SHALL declare a tool schema for the code interpreter integration including connection endpoints, optional language selection, and code/command/session fields.\n54: \n55: #### Scenario: Declared parameters match remote APIs\n56: \n57: - **GIVEN** `tools/agentcube-code-interpreter.yaml`\n58: - **WHEN** an operator configures the tool in Dify\n59: - **THEN** the schema SHALL require string parameters `router_url` and `workload_manager_url`, SHALL offer optional `language` as a select among `python`, `javascript`, and `typescript`, and SHALL allow optional `code`, `command`, `session_id`, `session_reuse` (boolean), and `code_interpreter_id`, each documented for human and LLM-oriented forms\n60: \n61: ---\n62: \n63: ### Requirement: Tool provider credential validation\n64: \n65: The system SHALL implement credential validation on the tool provider class and SHALL surface validation failures using the Dify tool provider error type.\n66: \n67: #### Scenario: Invalid credentials are rejected\n68: \n69: - **GIVEN** an instance of `AgentcubeCodeInterpreterProvider`\n70: - **WHEN** `_validate_credentials` encounters an error condition the implementer treats as invalid\n71: - **THEN** the provider SHALL raise `ToolProviderCredentialValidationError` with a string message derived from the failure\n72: \n73: #### Scenario: Successful validation completes quietly\n74: \n75: - **GIVEN** credentials that satisfy the provider’s validation rules\n76: - **WHEN** `_validate_credentials` runs\n77: - **THEN** the method SHALL return without raising\n78: \n79: ---\n80: \n81: ### Requirement: Tool invocation and JSON messaging\n82: \n83: The system SHALL implement the Agentcube code interpreter tool as a Dify `Tool` that delegates execution and returns structured JSON to the host.\n84: \n85: #### Scenario: Dify invokes the tool\n86: \n87: - **GIVEN** a configured tool invocation with parameters matching the schema\n88: - **WHEN** Dify calls `_invoke` on `AgentcubeCodeInterpreterTool`\n89: - **THEN** the tool SHALL call `execute(**tool_parameters)` and SHALL yield `create_json_message(result)` for the outcome\n90: \n91: ---\n92: \n93: ### Requirement: Tool execution API surface\n94: \n95: The system SHALL implement `execute` with parameters for router and workload manager URLs, optional language, session controls, and code or command execution, delegating to `agentcube.CodeInterpreterClient`.\n96: \n97: #### Scenario: Code or command runs against configured endpoints\n98: \n99: - **GIVEN** valid `router_url`, `workload_manager_url`, and optional `language` defaulting to `python`\n100: - **WHEN** the tool receives `code` and/or `command` with optional `session_id`, `session_reuse`, and `code_interpreter_id`\n101: - **THEN** the tool SHALL use the AgentCube Python SDK client to perform the corresponding remote operations and SHALL return a JSON-serializable result object suitable for `create_json_message`\n102: \n103: ---\n104: \n105: ### Requirement: Plugin Python dependencies\n106: \n107: The system SHALL pin compatible versions of `dify-plugin` and `agentcube-sdk` for reproducible installs.\n108: \n109: #### Scenario: Dependency bounds\n110: \n111: - **GIVEN** `integrations/dify-plugin/requirements.txt`\n112: - **WHEN** dependencies are installed in a clean environment\n113: - **THEN** installs SHALL satisfy `dify-plugin>=0.4.2,<0.5.0` and `agentcube-sdk>=0.0.10`\n114: \n115: ---\n116: \n117: ### Requirement: PCAP analyzer FastAPI service\n118: \n119: The system SHALL provide a FastAPI application that validates OpenAI-compatible configuration at startup, composes LangChain/LangGraph agents, and exposes an analysis endpoint for PCAP uploads.\n120: \n121: #### Scenario: Startup requires API key\n122: \n123: - **GIVEN** the process is started without a usable `OPENAI_API_KEY` (or equivalent configured API key)\n124: - **WHEN** the application completes startup hooks\n125: - **THEN** startup SHALL fail rather than serve requests without credentials\n126: \n127: #### Scenario: Analyze endpoint accepts PCAP input\n128: \n129: - **GIVEN** a running service with valid LLM configuration\n130: - **WHEN** a client calls `POST /analyze` with either an uploaded PCAP file or a `pcap_path` form field\n131: - **THEN** the handler SHALL return a body matching `AnalyzeResponse` including `script`, `results`, and `report`\n132: \n133: ---\n134: \n135: ### Requirement: PCAP analyzer configuration surface\n136: \n137: The system SHALL read runtime configuration from environment variables for the OpenAI-compatible API, model selection, and AgentCube sandbox parameters.\n138: \n139: #### Scenario: Defaults and overrides\n140: \n141: - **GIVEN** standard deployment environment variables\n142: - **WHEN** the service starts\n143: - **THEN** it SHALL use `OPENAI_API_BASE` defaulting to `https://api.siliconflow.cn/v1`, `OPENAI_MODEL` defaulting to `Qwen/QwQ-32B`, `CODEINTERPRETER_NAME` defaulting to `my-interpreter`, `SANDBOX_NAMESPACE` defaulting to `default`, and `SANDBOX_WARMUP_SEC` defaulting to `5`, while binding HTTP to `0.0.0.0:8000` as defined in the application\n144: \n145: ---\n146: \n147: ### Requirement: PCAP analyzer sandbox integration\n148: \n149: The system SHALL orchestrate PCAP analysis by planning and repairing scripts, executing them inside an AgentCube-backed sandbox via `SandboxRunner`, and aggregating results through reporter agents.\n150: \n151: #### Scenario: Sandbox runner executes commands\n152: \n153: - **GIVEN** a `SandboxRunner` constructed with interpreter name, namespace, and warmup duration\n154: - **WHEN** analysis logic invokes `run` with a shell command\n155: - **THEN** the runner SHALL execute the command in the remote sandbox context and SHALL return structured execution results for downstream LLM steps\n156: \n157: #### Scenario: File staging uses runner uploads\n158: \n159: - **GIVEN** a local PCAP path or bytes to analyze\n160: - **WHEN** the orchestration needs the artifact inside the sandbox workspace\n161: - **THEN** the system SHALL use `upload_file` or `upload_bytes` on `SandboxRunner` before executing analysis commands\n162: \n163: ---\n164: \n165: ### Requirement: PCAP analyzer container image\n166: \n167: The system SHALL build a container image that installs Python dependencies with `uv`, vendors the in-repo `agentcube` SDK copy, sets `PYTHONPATH`, exposes port 8000, and starts the FastAPI app via `uv run`.\n168: \n169: #### Scenario: Image entrypoint\n170: \n171: - **GIVEN** the `example/pcap-analyzer/Dockerfile` build context\n172: - **WHEN** the container runs without overriding the command\n173: - **THEN** the default command SHALL be `uv run pcap_analyzer.py` with `PYTHONPATH=\"/app\"` and port `8000` exposed\n174: \n175: ---\n176: \n177: ### Requirement: PCAP analyzer Kubernetes deployment\n178: \n179: The system SHALL supply a `Deployment` manifest that runs the analyzer image with resource requests/limits and environment variables wired from a Secret and plain env for AgentCube and model endpoints.\n180: \n181: #### Scenario: Deployment wiring\n182: \n183: - **GIVEN** `example/pcap-analyzer/deployment.yaml` applied to the cluster\n184: - **WHEN** the workload becomes ready\n185: - **THEN** the pod SHALL run image `pcap-analyzer:latest` (pull `IfNotPresent`), listen on TCP 8000, request `cpu: 200m` / `memory: 100Mi` and limit `cpu: 1` / `memory: 1Gi`, mount `OPENAI_API_KEY` from Secret `pcap-analyzer-secrets` key `openai-api-key`, and set `OPENAI_API_BASE`, `OPENAI_MODEL`, `WORKLOAD_MANAGER_URL`, `ROUTER_URL`, `CODEINTERPRETER_NAME`, `SANDBOX_NAMESPACE`, and `SANDBOX_WARMUP_SEC` as container environment variables\n186: \n187: #### Scenario: Process launch in cluster\n188: \n189: - **GIVEN** the deployment’s container specification\n190: - **WHEN** Kubernetes starts the container\n191: - **THEN** the command SHALL be `uv` with arguments `run pcap_analyzer.py`, matching local Docker behavior\n\n(End of file - total 191 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Integrations Specification\n\n## Purpose\n\nNormative requirements for the AgentCube Dify plugin integration and the PCAP analyzer example that uses AgentCube code interpreters and Kubernetes sandboxes.\n\n## Requirements\n\n### Requirement: Dify plugin bootstrap and runtime\n\nThe system SHALL expose a Dify-compatible Python plugin whose process entry runs the framework runner with a configured maximum request timeout.\n\n#### Scenario: Plugin process starts\n\n- **GIVEN** the plugin package is installed with compatible `dify-plugin` and `agentcube-sdk` versions\n- **WHEN** the platform starts the plugin using the manifest-declared entrypoint\n- **THEN** the plugin SHALL execute `main` which runs `Plugin(DifyPluginEnv(MAX_REQUEST_TIMEOUT=120)).run()` until the host stops it\n\n---\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/integrations/spec.md","time":{"start":1775838795113,"end":1775838795125}}}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1775838795153,"sessionID":"ses_287c2af5affeyN4a421B18EChw","part":{"id":"prt_d783d9577001kLt7VQaQ6p9gY7","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","messageID":"msg_d783d7b97001f7zhjRZyl7eHxs","sessionID":"ses_287c2af5affeyN4a421B18EChw","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":21209,"input":21088,"output":121,"reasoning":0,"cache":{"write":0,"read":0}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1775838798334,"sessionID":"ses_287c2af5affeyN4a421B18EChw","part":{"id":"prt_d783da1fd0015kIisnFWco1ZIS","messageID":"msg_d783d95a6001qUWoynVyGecN89","sessionID":"ses_287c2af5affeyN4a421B18EChw","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1775838827677,"sessionID":"ses_287c2af5affeyN4a421B18EChw","part":{"id":"prt_d783daeb7001Zc2oZqpKSwkVmE","messageID":"msg_d783d95a6001qUWoynVyGecN89","sessionID":"ses_287c2af5affeyN4a421B18EChw","type":"text","text":"I'll create the delta-spec.md file for AR-001 in OpenSpec format with GIVEN/WHEN/THEN scenarios based on the client-go specification and project context.","time":{"start":1775838827674,"end":1775838827674}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775838827792,"sessionID":"ses_287c2af5affeyN4a421B18EChw","part":{"id":"prt_d783e149c001o4e2QQOw77dGDK","messageID":"msg_d783d95a6001qUWoynVyGecN89","sessionID":"ses_287c2af5affeyN4a421B18EChw","type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_tool-21cf1a9b835e47a096dc96170afbae0d","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"content":"# AR-001 Delta Specification: CRD AgentRuntime 类型定义\n\n## Purpose\n\nDefine Go type definitions and Kubernetes CRD registration for the `AgentRuntime` custom resource in the `runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh/v1alpha1` API group, including integration with the generated client-go library and proper API machinery support.\n\n## Requirements\n\n### Requirement: AgentRuntime type metadata and API group version\n\nThe system SHALL define `AgentRuntime` as a Kubernetes custom resource with `runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh` API group, `v1alpha1` version, kind `AgentRuntime`, and resource plural `agentruntimes`.\n\n#### Scenario: Type metadata reflects GVR mapping\n- **GIVEN** a Kubernetes API server resolving the CRD type\n- **WHEN** the `TypeMeta` fields are inspected\n- **THEN** `APIVersion` is `runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh/v1alpha1` and `Kind` is `AgentRuntime`\n\n#### Scenario: Resource plural matches client-go expectations\n- **GIVEN** a typed client for `AgentRuntime`\n- **WHEN** constructing a `GroupVersionResource` from the type\n- **THEN** resource name is `agentruntimes` in plural form\n\n### Requirement: AgentRuntimeSpec structure with required fields\n\nThe system SHALL define `AgentRuntimeSpec` struct with required fields: `PodTemplate` of type `*SandboxTemplate`, `SessionTimeout` of type `*metav1.Duration`, and `MaxSessionDuration` of type `*metav1.Duration`.\n\n#### Scenario: Spec requires pod template\n- **GIVEN** a new `AgentRuntime` object being created\n- **WHEN** the spec is populated\n- **THEN** `PodTemplate` must be non-nil and contains the sandbox pod template\n\n#### Scenario: Duration fields use metav1 types\n- **GIVEN** an existing `AgentRuntime` with timeouts configured\n- **WHEN** the spec is serialized to YAML\n- **THEN** `SessionTimeout` and `MaxSessionDuration` serialize as duration strings\n\n### Requirement: AgentRuntimeStatus with conditions support\n\nThe system SHALL define `AgentRuntimeStatus` struct with optional `Conditions` field of type `[]metav1.Condition` for tracking runtime state transitions.\n\n#### Scenario: Status conditions are optional\n- **GIVEN** a newly created `AgentRuntime` resource\n- **WHEN** status is initially empty\n- **THEN** resource creation succeeds without requiring conditions\n\n#### Scenario: Condition updates follow Kubernetes conventions\n- **GIVEN** a controller managing `AgentRuntime` lifecycle\n- **WHEN** transitioning between states (e.g., Creating → Running)\n- **THEN** conditions are added with appropriate types, reasons, and transition timestamps\n\n### Requirement: AgentRuntimeList type for collection operations\n\nThe system SHALL define `AgentRuntimeList` as a standard Kubernetes list type containing `[]AgentRuntime` items and standard list metadata.\n\n#### Scenario: List type supports pagination\n- **GIVEN** multiple `AgentRuntime` resources in a namespace\n- **WHEN** `List` operation is called with `ListOptions.Limit`\n- **THEN** response returns an `AgentRuntimeList` with `Continue` token when more items exist\n\n### Requirement: Scheme registration for serialization\n\nThe system SHALL register `AgentRuntime` and `AgentRuntimeList` types in the Kubernetes scheme for proper JSON/YAML serialization and deserialization.\n\n#### Scenario: YAML deserialization produces correct Go types\n- **GIVEN** a YAML file containing `kind: AgentRuntime` in the `runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh/v1alpha1` API group\n- **WHEN** the YAML is decoded using the registered scheme\n- **THEN** an `AgentRuntime` struct instance is created with correct field mappings\n\n#### Scenario: List kind maps to AgentRuntimeList\n- **GIVEN** a YAML file containing `kind: AgentRuntimeList`\n- **WHEN** the YAML is decoded\n- **THEN** an `AgentRuntimeList` struct instance is created with items as `[]AgentRuntime`\n\n### Requirement: CRD subresources support\n\nThe system SHALL enable status subresource on `AgentRuntime` to allow independent updates to status without modifying spec.\n\n#### Scenario: Status update does not modify spec\n- **GIVEN** an existing `AgentRuntime` with both spec and status\n- **WHEN** a status-only update is performed via API server\n- **THEN** only status fields change and spec remains unmodified\n\n#### Scenario: Status and spec have independent versioning\n- **GIVEN** a controller updating status\n- **WHEN** status changes multiple times\n- **THEN** each status update increments `metadata.generation` independently of spec modifications\n\n### Requirement: Default values for spec fields\n\nThe system SHALL define kubebuilder markers to set default values: `SessionTimeout` defaults to `\"15m\"` and `MaxSessionDuration` defaults to `\"8h\"`.\n\n#### Scenario: Missing timeout fields receive defaults\n- **GIVEN** an `AgentRuntime` created without explicit timeout values\n- **WHEN** the resource is created via API\n- **THEN** `SessionTimeout` is set to `15m` and `MaxSessionDuration` to `8h` automatically\n\n#### Scenario: Explicit values override defaults\n- **GIVEN** an `AgentRuntime` created with custom timeout values\n- **WHEN** the resource is created\n- **THEN** the explicit values are preserved and defaults are not applied\n\n### Requirement: OpenAPI validation for spec fields\n\nThe system SHALL generate OpenAPI v3 schema for `AgentRuntime` to enable validation of field types, required fields, and constraints.\n\n#### Scenario: Required field validation\n- **GIVEN** a request creating `AgentRuntime` without required `PodTemplate`\n- **WHEN** the API server validates the request\n- **THEN** validation fails with error indicating `podTemplate` is required\n\n#### Scenario: Type validation for duration fields\n- **GIVEN** a request creating `AgentRuntime` with invalid duration format\n- **WHEN** the API server validates the request\n- **THEN** validation fails with error about invalid duration format\n\n### Requirement: Print columns for kubectl readability\n\nThe system SHALL configure additional printer columns for `kubectl get` output, including `Age` derived from `metadata.creationTimestamp`.\n\n#### Scenario: Age column displays correctly\n- **GIVEN** an `AgentRuntime` resource that was created 5 minutes ago\n- **WHEN** `kubectl get agentruntimes` is executed\n- **THEN** the Age column shows `5m` or equivalent time duration\n\n### Requirement: CRD status storage optimization\n\nThe system SHALL use status subresource to ensure status updates are stored efficiently and do not trigger spec reconciliation unnecessarily.\n\n#### Scenario: Frequent status updates\n- **GIVEN** a controller updating `AgentRuntime` status every 30 seconds\n- **WHEN** multiple status updates occur\n- **THEN** each update only writes to status subresource and does not trigger full reconciliation\n\n### Requirement: Type registration in code-generation\n\nThe system SHALL ensure `AgentRuntime` types are included in the client-go code-generation pipeline to produce typed clients, informers, and listers.\n\n#### Scenario: Typed client operations work\n- **GIVEN** a `Clientset` instance from generated client-go code\n- **WHEN** calling `client.RuntimeV1alpha1().AgentRuntimes(namespace).Create`\n- **THEN** the operation succeeds with proper type safety and returns an `AgentRuntime` pointer\n\n#### Scenario: Informer factory recognizes AgentRuntime\n- **GIVEN** a `SharedInformerFactory` for the runtime API group\n- **WHEN** `Runtime().V1alpha1().AgentRuntimes().Informer()` is called\n- **THEN** an informer watching `agentruntimes` resources is returned\n\n### Requirement: JSON tag naming convention\n\nThe system SHALL use camelCase JSON tags for all fields to match Kubernetes API conventions and client-go expectations.\n\n#### Scenario: JSON serialization uses camelCase\n- **GIVEN** an `AgentRuntime` struct populated with Go fields\n- **WHEN** serialized to JSON\n- **THEN** the JSON keys are camelCase (e.g., `podTemplate`, `sessionTimeout`, `maxSessionDuration`)\n\n### Requirement: DeepCopy methods for safety\n\nThe system SHALL implement `DeepCopy`, `DeepCopyInto`, `DeepCopyObject` methods for `AgentRuntime` to support safe copying in controllers.\n\n#### Scenario: DeepCopy creates independent instance\n- **GIVEN** an `AgentRuntime` instance with populated fields\n- **WHEN** `DeepCopy` is called\n- **THEN** the returned copy is independent and modifications to the copy do not affect the original\n\n### Requirement: Validation markers for fields\n\nThe system SHALL use kubebuilder validation markers to enforce constraints on spec fields where applicable.\n\n#### Scenario: Duration fields validate format\n- **GIVEN** an `AgentRuntime` with `SessionTimeout` set to invalid duration\n- **WHEN** the resource is submitted to the API server\n- **THEN** validation fails with error indicating invalid duration format\n\n### Requirement: Label selector support for listing\n\nThe system SHALL support standard Kubernetes label selectors when listing `AgentRuntime` resources.\n\n#### Scenario: Label selector filters results\n- **GIVEN** multiple `AgentRuntime` resources with different labels\n- **WHEN** `List` is called with a label selector matching a specific label\n- **THEN** only resources matching the selector are returned\n\n### Requirement: Watch support for controller integration\n\nThe system SHALL support watch operations on `AgentRuntime` resources to enable controllers to react to changes efficiently.\n\n#### Scenario: Watch events notify of changes\n- **GIVEN** a watch stream established on `AgentRuntime` resources\n- **WHEN** a new `AgentRuntime` is created\n- **THEN** the watch stream receives an ADDED event with the new resource","filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/changes/AR-001/delta-spec.md"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/changes/AR-001/delta-spec.md","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/changes/AR-001/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775838827778,"end":1775838827789}}}}
